surveys <- read.csv("data/portal_data_joined.csv")
ggplot(data = surveys)

ggplot(data = surveys, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length))

ggplot(data = surveys, aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# Assign plot to a variable
surveys_plot <- ggplot(data = surveys, 
                       mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length))

# Draw the plot
surveys_plot + 
    geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

# This is the correct syntax for adding layers
surveys_plot +
  geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

###What are the relative strengths and weaknesses of a hexagonal bin plot compared to a scatter plot? ### This plot is benefical for visualizing large data sets that may be overplotted in point graphs. This may not be as useful when looking for overall trends in large data sets.

ggplot(data = surveys, aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point()
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = surveys, aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1)
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = surveys, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1, color = "blue")
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = surveys, mapping = aes(x = weight, y = hindfoot_length)) +
    geom_point(alpha = 0.1, aes(color = species_id))
## Warning: Removed 4048 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

###Challenge 2 ###Use what you just learned to create a scatter plot of weight over species_id with the plot types showing in different colors. Is this a good way to show this type of data?

ggplot(data = surveys, 
       mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
   geom_point(aes(color = plot_type))
## Warning: Removed 2503 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

ggplot(data = surveys, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_boxplot()
## Warning: Removed 2503 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

ggplot(data = surveys, mapping = aes(x = species_id, y = weight)) +
    geom_boxplot(alpha = 0) +
    geom_jitter(alpha = 0.3, color = "tomato")
## Warning: Removed 2503 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).
## Warning: Removed 2503 rows containing missing values (geom_point).
